This paper deals with the impact of collective online participation on individual privacy, which is a topic that falls under the broad category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also uses machine learning algorithms to uncover personal traits from apparently harmless features, which is related to the sub-category of cybernetics (cs.CY). The analysis of the edit history of Wikipedia involves large-scale data processing and statistical analysis, which is relevant to the sub-category of software development (cs.SD). The paper also discusses the implications of its findings for policy makers, which is related to the sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). Finally, the paper uses natural language processing techniques to analyze the content of Wikipedia edits, which is relevant to the sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR).
